desc.description: Brynn Elliott - Internet You (Live Performance)Some parents keep their kids on a limited amount of TV per day. With Brynn Elliott, it was the radio. As a child, the singer behind "Might Not Like Me" was addicted to the pop station of her native Atlanta area, and had to sneak listening time after curfew hours. Looks like she picked up plenty of pointers. With a knack for catchy melodies and insightful lyrics, Elliott's songs cut to the heart. The tunes on her 'Time Of Our Lives' EP were inspired by the philosophy classes she took while while a student at Harvard. Armed only with an acoustic guitar, we had her perform a couple of them live; both "Internet You" and "Tongue Tied" came out great. Check 'em out and see if you have a new fave on your hands. desc.description: King Calaway  No Matter What - Vevo Live Performance They come from the US and the UK. They've played cruise ships, studio sessions, and honky-tonks. They've got the kind of energy that lights up their music, and the kind of musicianship that unearths a song's essence. And there's definitely no doubt about their vocal skills - when the guys in King Calaway unite their voices, everything seems right in the world. Caleb Miller, Chris Deaton, Simon Dumas, Jordan Harvey, Chad Michael Jervis and Austin Luther haven't played together long, but their first moves suggest plenty of success. The guys connected in Nashville, where twang and pop mix freely, but they've got their eyes on impressing listeners around the globe. The Calaway squad rolled into Vevo for a couple performances from their self-titled debut EP, "World For Two" and "No Matter What." Long story short? They rocked it. desc.description: Ruel: Three Thoughts on Expensive ClothesIt started with James Bay's "Let It Go." Sydney tween Ruel Van Dijt recorded himself singing the UK hero's hit, and shared it with a producer. The producer had some industry juice, loved the track, and...Bam! A career was off and running thanks to a husky voice that has a rather persuasive R&B quality. Since then, Ruel's earned himself some other nice breaks, too. He's toured with Angus and Julia Stone, collected a big handful of critical raves, and got a bit of dap from new-artist supporter, Elton John. Along the way he cut a beat-box version of Rag'n'Bone Man's "Human" that you've just gotta hear, and has dropped a very cool vid for his "Younger" track. Now 15 years old, Ruel is increasingly in the spotlight. So fashion is often on his mind. He's got opinions about that. "Style doesn't need to be high-end," says the man who feel comfortable in sweats and a hoodie. "People I look up to the most are the people who really don't give a shit. They throw all the rules out the window. Like Tyler the Creator - he's kinda dressing up like a granddad, but he looks so dope." See what else Ruel has to say about expensive clothes in our 'Three Thoughts' chat.Producer: Priya MinhasEditor: Lika Kumoi Watch Ruel videos: https://bit.ly/2OsvPD5 Vevo http://facebook.com/vevo http://twitter.com/vevo http://instagram.com/vevo  Ruel:http://www.instagram.com/oneruel  http://www.facebook.com/oneruelhttp://www.twitter.com/oneruelhttp://www.soundcloud.com/oneruelhttp://vevo.ly/1aqas0
desc.title: Ruel - Three Thoughts on Expensive Clothes

desc.description: Mario...On Shadow WorkR&B fiends know the power of Mario's voice, and through the years, it's only gotten more and more expressive. "Let Me Love You" proved the impact his voice can have on fans. These days, he's just coming back from a little break, and with the video for "Drowning," reminds just how rich his craft can be. His new 'Dancing Shadows' album arrives on October 5, so we invited him in to expound on balancing life's dark and light sides. He recounts a serious childhood and early career success in a heartfelt chat. desc.description: "Little Light" Official Performance | VevoAmos Lee has been one of our go-to singer-songwriters for more than a decade now. His lyrics always reveal some kind of truth that we all know but can't exactly put into words, and his melodies are indelible. Settle into a Lee show, and soon you'll see: whether its "Arms of a Woman," "Sweet Pea" or "Keep It Loose, Keep It Tight," the audience can't helping singing along with their hero. "Little Light" was inspired by the perseverance of an eight-year-old girl who Lee met through the Melodic Caring Project, a group that steams concerts to kids who are quarantined because of illness. Watch him roll the song, which is from his new album, 'My New Moon.' desc.description: After three decades of thriving in the rock realm, Lenny Kravitz pulled up from a massive tour a few years ago and scratched his head. He wasn't sure what the next move was, and worse, he didn't even feel inspired to carry on. So it was chill time. Everyone deserves that, and often it's enough to revitalize the creativity. But even when he hit the Bahamas to start tracking the music that's on his new 'Raise Vibration,' there was still a reticence in the air. Frustrating. Then the elements of "Low" popped into his head in a dream, and then more songs came while he was slumbering. Dude dreamed his whole damned record. Watch the man who brought us "Are You Gonna Go My Way," "Again," "Fly Away," and "Let Love Rule," discuss the recording process and the emotions that drive the songs in our exclusive interview. desc.title: Lenny Kravitz - Lenny Kravitz Talks ‘Raise Vibration,’ And Why Love Still Rules

desc.description: Amy Shark has told interviewers that she wrote her first song as a form of therapy - forget about a hit or career, it was just a way for a teen to articulate her feelings while strumming the guitar. But the Aussie singer with the global reach, who has recently brought fans beloved tracks such as "Adore" and "I Said Hi," did carry on and make a sizable impact. Her "Spits on Girls" turned lots of heads and got a buzz going in 2014. This year she dropped 'Love Monster,' an album full of catchy songs that unpack a wealth of emotions. Shark has referenced her music as "gritty pop" - it's not a shiny as some of competition's. But it is impactful. From a bedroom on the Gold Coast to taking home the Queensland Music award for Pop Song of the Year - nice trajectory. But moving forward and clocking victories can be slow going sometimes. As part of our 'Three Thoughts' series, we had Shark stop by to explain how perseverance is just as important as inspiration when it comes to sustaining a career in music. desc.description: My self-titled EP featuring "Karma" & "Medicine" is out now!!! Listen here : http://queennaija.lnk.to/EPYD-----"Medicine" Official Performance | VevoLook into the roots of strong R&B vocalists, and you may find they spent time singing in church. The modern soul approach of Queen Naija, which can be heard on tracks such as "Bad Boy," "Mama's Hand" and "Medicine," is partially due to getting schooled early on - she was part of a choir as a child in her native Detroit. That was way before she became a YouTube hero, of course. For the last few years, she's been pleasing fans by inviting them into her all aspects of her life as a wildly popular vlogger. Boasting three million subscribers, her YT channel has focused on delivering personal candor to an ever-growing fan base. When she and her husband split last year, it prompted her to hit the studio and not only vent some frustration but stand up for women everywhere. "Medicine" busted the the 22-year-old to the next level success that she's riding right now. Her follow-up track on the same subject, "Karma," is just as revealing, with a message attached. "I'm just letting him know, I might be sad right now, you might be happy, but the table's gonna turn. While it makes me feel good that other women can relate to what i'm writing," she said during our recent performance/interview, "it makes me feel bad that they have to go through it." Watch our exclusive performance of "Medicine" right now and share it with other Naija fans. desc.description: Ya gotta start somewhere. Mason Ramsey kicked things off at a Walmart in southern Illinois. Earlier this summer, a video of the 11-year-old singing Hank Williams' "Lovesick Blues" in the store aisle went viral, and between his interpretive skills and his off-the-charts cuteness, he's become a recording artist. Ramsey has been singing and yodeling for a while, actually. He's participated in regional talent contests and earned a area-wide buzz, starting his Hank homages at the age of four. The woman who captured his Walmart performance had shot him previously in other locales. Since that now-famous gig, he's been on 'Ellen', performed at the Grand Ole Opry, and even shared the Coachella stage with EDM artist Whethan. Now he's signed to Atlantic records. He came by Vevo to sing a couple of non-Hank tunes, "Famous" and "The Way I See It," and his charisma was right up front with his voice. desc.description: G Herbo - Three Thoughts on Fatherhood Nothin' easy about comin' up in Chicago's South Shore, especially 'round the hood known as Terror Town. G Herbo's records reflect the full-on street perspectives that make his hard-hitting tracks deliver so much lyrical clout. Lil Herb has absorbed all the conflict around him, and sprays out portraits of city life that are riddled with the constant sense of danger Chicago carries with it these days. He's connected with Windy City heroes in the last year or so, sharing the mic with Common, Chance the Rapper and Vic Mensa. And of course his pal Lil Bibby, a South Shore homey who like Herb also is part of XXL's Freshman Class alumni. Last year's 'Humble Beast' made good on all the promise of his previous mixtapes, with "Red Snow" and "I Like" leading the charge. Now fans are knocked out by his 'Swervo' album, and the videos for "Focused" and the title track. To celebrate its arrival we had him come by a share his perspective on a subject important to him: fatherhood. "My dad did everything to be supportive. As a man you gotta make sacrifices for your family. So I do think about what he did for us." See what he thinks about changing diapers to enhance artistic drive in 'Three Thoughts.' desc.description: You heard the Earth shake a bit when Clipse dropped its 'Lord Willin'' album back in 2002, didn't ya? It was a big one, and the work Pusha T and No Malice did with Pharrell Williams is gonna last a couple lifetimes. So's the strong stuff the Bronx-born, Virginia-raised MC has made on his own - ever since 'My Name Is My Name' arrived under the GOOD Music banner, the company that King Push is now the president of. In May he dropped his latest disc, DAYTONA, a collab with his business partner and creative brother, Kanye West. The pair worked on it in Wyoming, and as you might expect, Ye had a unique production process. In our exclusive interview, we take Pusha T to Staten Island to get his POV on a key influence, Raekwon's 'Only Built 4 Cuban Linx..." See what he says about Shaolin culture, 'The Purple Tape' and how the classics shaped the feel of the tracks on 'DAYTONA.' desc.description: Three Thoughts on Self Care There's been a lotta bouncin' around in Wifisfuneral's life. 21-year-old MC Isaiah Rivera has caught some major buzz from his SoundCloud tracks and hard-hitting mixtapes such as 'Black Heart Revenge' and 'When Hell Falls." Growing up in Palm Beach after spending his childhood in the Bronx, Rivera has said that he often longed for the support of his estranged dad, a NYC battle-rapper whose profession helped inspire his son to pick up a mic. As a Florida teen, hip-hop was everything to WiFi, but he found himself battling drug use and contemplating suicide. Those feelings of confusion and despair have helped fuel his art, and he's turned blunt rhymes into eloquent emotional statements. He's cited Three 6 Mafia and Lil Wayne as inspirations, but through the last two years, he's honed his sound into something truly personal - one reason why he made it to XXL's Freshman 2018 Freshman Class list. You can hear those latest efforts on 'Ethernet,' the WiFi's new album featuring "25 Lighters" and "100 Ways." We invited him participate in our 'Three Thoughts' series, and he blew through a list of reasons of how important it is to take care of yourself physically and mentally. desc.description: Dave-1 and P-Thugg, the funky duo behind the Canadian synth-pop band Chromeo, took the time to talk about their fifth studio release, 'Head Over Heels,' and its cover art with their Art Director Charlotte Delarue. By constantly blending different genres and styles, the band is creating music with layers to unfold and excite fans. This made it paramount that the album's artwork reflects that sensibility by mixing the low-brow with the high-brow and injecting their signature sense of humor. The band also takes a moment to self-critique, subverting their history of covers displaying female legs by shaving their own and donning a pair of pumps. "Stop having that dichotomy between men and women," explains Dave 1,  "we were just like 'eh, that doesn't resonate with us in 2018 anymore.'"Producer: Priya MinhasDirector: Chase SmithWatch Chromeo videos: https://www.youtube.com/user/ChromeoVEVOVevo http://facebook.com/vevohttp://twitter.com/vevohttp://instagram.com/vevoChromeohttps://www.instagram.com/chromeo/https://www.facebook.com/chromeo/https://twitter.com/Chromeo

desc.description: Born in Jamaica and raised in the Bronx, HoodCelebrityy made a strong impression when she dropped "The Takeover" on SoundCloud last year. In a flash, lots of heads were turning toward the twentysomething MC whose blend of trap and dancehall had an instantly seductive vibe, and whose confidence was obvious with every rhyme she spit. Her 'Can't Believe It's Just a Girl' mixtape bolstered all the props that she was receiving, and early shout-outs from future stars like Cardi B further and features with French Montana cemented her cred. Fast forward and HoodCelebrityy's rolling with Epic and flexing in the video for "Walking Trophy," a hot little track that's all about pushing posi vibes and stressing self-worth. She also has the song "Find My Way Out" on the 'Superfly' soundtrack. The singer has said it's about a woman who knows she's beautiful without men having to tell her. In our 'Three Thoughts' interview, HoodCelebrityy explains how to live your best life by "burstin' the bubble" of other people's expectations and simply being yourself. desc.description: :60 With Randy Blythe of Lamb of God.Few bands erupt with kind of power that Lamb of God has demonstrated in the last two decades. The metal masters are hailed not only for their punishing mix of guitar wail and rhythmic thud, but thoughtful lyrics that scrutinize the prevailing power structures that guide us all to some degree. The group -  Randy Blythe, Mark Morton, John Campbell, Chris Adler and Willie Adler - began its life under the name Kill The Priest - and for their latest album, 'Legion: XX,' they've created a collection of cool covers that features some of their favorite bands from their mid-90s roots. Agnostic Front, Cro-Mags, Quicksand, Ministry, Bad Brains, Melvins and more are addressed, and KTP's video for their update of Big Black's "Kerosene" is must-see portrait of mayhem in suburbia. Kill The Priest singer Randy Blythe submitted to our rapid-fire interview, and we learned a few things, including being a Dairy Queen janitor, cheating in school, his presidential running mate, and his best celeb impression. desc.description: It's not unusual to meet a life-long bestie in college. That's def what happened to the women of OSHUN. Thandi and Niambi connected during orientation at New York University, and soon enough they were making very impressive music together. They named themselves after a West African diety of "sweet waters," and their woke lyrics and soulful grooves are all about nudging elements of neo-soul and hip-hop into a singular spot. You've probably heard their "Sango" - pretty much irresistible. desc.description: Great Music, Bad Behavior: Inside 'Meet Me In The Bathroom,' And New York's Last Real Rock Scene. (Vevo) New Yorkâ€™s music scene is well known as action central. From punk in the â€˜70s to hip-hop in the â€˜80s, sounds rise and fall, always introducing us to valuable new artists. The early 2000s, with bands such as the Strokes, Interpol, and the Yeah Yeah Yeahs making a name or themselves and revitalizing the alt-rock lingo, was a particularly valuable epoch â€“ a time when audience and artist co-mingled to create a full-on social subculture. One of the best music books of 2017, Lizzy Goodmanâ€™s â€˜Meet Me in the Bathroomâ€™ is an overview of that era, an oral history that spans 2001-2011 and covers the musicâ€™s gritty beginnings, the effect of 9/11 and the internet, the drugs and debauchery, and the love of music that fueled the scene. To understand the nuances a bit better, Vevoâ€™s Kim Taylor Bennett connected with author Goodman, DJ Justine D (a club mainstay of the era), and Interpol guitarist Daniel Kessler at East Village mainstay 2A for an extended round-table chat about what drove the culture,neglected cool bands and local scandals, and whether it was the magical artistic time that many people recall. desc.description: When 'The God Complex' bubbled up in 2014 it was pretty obvious that GoldLink was gonna make a mark on hip-hop. Twelve months later, along with Fetty Wap and Vince Staples, he popped up on XXL's Freshman Class list and the buzz was on. Now he's clocking critical acclaim, and pleasing a quickly-growing audience with tracks such as "Dance On Me", "Fall In Love", and "Crew". D'Anthony Carlos came up in the DMV, moving from DC to Maryland to Virginia and back as a kid. The percussion grooves of the District's classic go-go music were often in the air when he was growing up, and the 23-year-old's current records have a deep rhythmic thrust as well as a yen for experimental sampling. Because his rhymes speak to the social and political culture that surrounds him, we headed to DC to make a portrait that marks some of his day-to-day inspirations. 'We Are The Flowers in Your Dustbin' catches the MC at home, with his squad, and candidly explaining how he got to where he is right now.Producers: Jayson Rodriguez, Cameron RobertEditor: Kevin Rose GoldLink on Vevo - https://www.vevo.com/artist/goldlinkhttp://facebook.com/vevohttp://twitter.com/vevohttp://instagram.com/vevohttp://vevo.tumblr.comGoldLink:http://www.goldlink.infohttps://www.twitter.com/goldlinkhttps://www.facebook.com/goldlinkhttps://www.instagram.com/goldlinkhttp://vevo.ly/9l3IOt

desc.description: Halsey on Losing Herself to Find Herself Again. 2017One of Halsey's key artistic traits is the candor that drives both her music and her relationship with her audience.  Whether the subject is politics or romance, the singer behind "Ghost," "Colors" and "New Americana" always cuts to the chase, unearthing emotions that are often brushed aside by others. Her new 'hopeless fountain kingdom' album was written and recorded in the wake of a breakup, the "misadventure" of star-crossed lovers as she reveals in album's "Prologue." Halsey recently performed the songs for the first time ever at our Vevo Presents show in LA, and in our exclusive interview she sat down with Kim Taylor Bennett to elaborate on their origins, plot twists, and meanings. Along the way she explained how Baz Luhrmann's 'Romeo + Juliet' helped her shape the narrative, how she crafted the traits of her lovers Luna and Solace, and how she had to come to grips with herself when her ex was no longer in the daily picture. Big questions and intriguing options sprouted immediately, and she tells Bennett all about them. "When I'm making a record, I want my fans to know the characters and know the story," she says. "It's kind of liberating, being so honest. Because it keeps me being honest with myself." desc.description: Places that Shape K.Flay. 2017Kristine Flaherty fell into the world of hip-hop while a student at Stamford more than a decade ago. As K.Flay she became an inspired badass, writing rhymes, dropping mixtapes and finding herself in a music career heralded for its emotional candor and lyrical articulation, what Rolling Stone once called a "rebel chick charm." Through the years her vision widened and her sound grew. These days there's plenty alt-rock attitude guiding the ship. Her 'Life Is a Dog' and 'Crush Me' releases were critically celebrated, and her new 'Every  Where Is Some Where' album brings us powerful videos such as "Blood in the Cut" and "High Enough." To celebrate its arrival K.Flay stopped by to tell us about some of the locales that have made an impact on her work. 'Places That Shape K.Flay' finds her explaining spots such as her parents' basement as a teen and a San Francisco nightclub as a college student. Other cool places, too. Find out what they mean to her. desc.description: 'Church In These Streets' Available Now: iTunes: http://smarturl.it/iChurch?IQid=VEVOStream On Spotify: http://smarturl.it/sChurch?IQid=VEVOGoogle Play: http://smarturl.it/gChurch?IQid=VEVOAmazon: http://smarturl.it/aChurch?IQid=VEVOI would like to take this time to ADDRESS the Street Disciples and Congregation to express my concerns and frustrations on what's going on in our communities all over the world today.With the poverty level at an all time high, it's damn near impossible for one to take care of him or herself without the possibility of prison or death. You have law enforcement officials gunning down unarmed black men. You have misinformed young American gunning down unarmed women, children and men in churches, movie theaters and public events. There's a war going on, but you have to ask yourself, who is the enemy?They ask why you black males are so militant? My answer to that would be because they are making us soldiers. Soldiers in a war on humanity. We have nothing to lose and everything to fight for. We are fighting for our people; we are fighting for our right to live.We die to claim our streets and hoods when we don't own as much as a mail box. That tells me one thing - If we all were on the same page and had the same cause, there is nothing in the world we can't change or make happen.They ask us why we hustle? To feed our families; to take care of our households; to pay our bills on time. Just like any other American. The only problem is there's not enough jobs and opportunities for everyone. As a matter of fact, people are being laid off at an alarming rate.Black men getting out of prison try to turn over a new leaf in life, but are placed on parole so they are not able to find employment. They are forced to return to the only way they know to survive. That means sacrificing his freedom and life for his family's survival.You may call him a criminal, a felon, a societal problem or all the above, but I see someone that is noble and honorable. I see a leader. Malcolm X and Dr. Martin Luther King died for what they believed in; so did Bob Marley. They all have a cause and wanted to make a difference in this crazy world.When an individual would do anything for his or her community and the people in it, that is a Godly act. Not in the biblical sense, but in the sense of the word.We are all Gods in our own right. We all have the ability and the power to change the things around us. We all have the ability to affect lives; to raise our sons and daughters to become Kings and Queens; Leaders and Prophets. To make a difference on Earth while they are here.I know you may be reading this and thinking to yourself, why so dark? Why so sinister? When in fact, it is the exact opposite.I recently revealed a short visual on Instagram, which showed a black cat walking past a door with a cross painted on it. Let me take the time to explain the meaning of this.You see the black cat is something weâ€™ve always associated with bad luck and evil. My grandmother used to tell me don't cross a black cats path because it was bad luck. However, she also told me that there was a tooth fairy who left me a dollar every time I lost a tooth. You know where I'm going with this...The truth is if you see a cat walking as if it has a destination, it more than likely is following its own path. The question is are you following yours?And the crosses were used to symbolize warding off death and evil and the protection of what's inside the doors - Our loved ones; our communities; our churches, our children and most of all our souls. So you might start seeing these crosses any and everywhere.Dreams don't expire - they just multiply and If yours dreams don't scare, then you ain't dreaming BIG enough...But what do I know...I'm just a Black man that came from nothing who was never given anything and for that matter, never asked for anything. But I was willing to sacrifice my freedom and my livelihood for my beliefs. And that act alone is what makes us GODS...This is coming from a place of passion and not ignorance. To Be Continued...Friday, November 13th.Sincerely Yours, Pastor YoungAmen. Amen.Jeezy - GOD (Audio) (Explicit)http://vevo.ly/slTD9b

desc.description: Khalid - Better Official Live Performance (Vevo X) No way around it, Khalid has been charming everyone who has heard his music since "Coaster," "Let's Go" and "Reasons" announced his arrival a couple years now. When the El Paso native's 'American Teen' album became the center of attention from critics, fans and Grammy bigwigs. With the recent arrival of his 'Suncity' EP, the singer shows us that he's up for investigating all sorts of ideas. While they sound kin to his previous work, tracks such as "Motion" and "Better" look around corners, test new waters, take a chance or two. Moving the conversation forward is pure Khalid, so we were thrilled when our LIFT alum said yes to trying unique updates of his newest songs. Tucked away in an LA cottage, our Vevo X session caught him rolling through performances of "Vertigo" and other "Better." Backed by a luminous string quartet on the former and a handful of great singers on the latter, this cozy approach gives us a great perspective on Khalid's newest music. Share "Better" and "Vertigo" with other Khalid fans.
